Question 3.2

world %>% 
  filter(!is.na(co2)) %>% 
  filter(name == "United States of America" | name == "China" | name == "India" | name == "Chile" | name == "Austria") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(time, co2, col=factor(name))) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Time", y = "CO2 Emissions", col = "Countries\n")

This line plot displays five different countries and their CO2 emissions over the years from 1960 to 2019. Looking at the graph, it shows me that China is the largest emitter of CO2 since 2016 with the United States coming in second. India seems to be increasing their CO2 emissions over the years as well, but not as much as China and the US. On the other hand, Austria and Chile seems to emit little to no CO2 compared to the other three countries on the graph.

Question 3.3

(5pt) Now let’s analyze the CO2 emissions per capita (co2_PC). Make a similar plot of the same countries. What does this figure suggest?

world %>% 
  filter(!is.na(co2_PC)) %>% 
  filter(name == "United States of America" | name == "China" | name == "India" | name == "Chile" | name == "Austria") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(time, co2_PC, col=factor(name))) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Time", y = "CO2 Emissions (per capita)", col = "Countries\n")

After analyzing the line plot above, it tells me that the US average citizens contribute to the most CO2 emissions per capita out of the other countries listed. Austria’s, Chile’s, China’s and India’s citizens do not emit as much CO2 per capita on average as US citizens.

## 1 Africa      1.20
## 2 Americas    4.80
## 3 Asia        6.47
## 4 Europe      6.64
## 5 Oceania     4.57

Looking at the average emissions per capita during the year 2016, the region that emitted the most was Europe with 6.64 CO2. The lowest emissions during the same year was Africa with 1.20 CO2 per capita.

Question 3.5

average_pc <- world %>% 
  select(region, co2_PC, time) %>%
  filter(!is.na(region), time %in% c("1960", "2016")) %>% 
  group_by(region, time) %>% 
  summarise(avgCO2 = mean(co2_PC, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'region'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
ggplot(average_pc, aes(region, avgCO2, fill=factor(time))) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "Average CO2 Emissions Per Capita Across The Continents",
           x = "Continents",
           y = "Average CO2 Per Capita",
           fill = "Time (Year)")

Part 4

Question 4.1

gdp_1960 <- world %>% 
  group_by(name) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(GDP_PC), !is.na(lifeExpectancy)) %>% 
  select(region, GDP_PC, lifeExpectancy, totalPopulation, time) %>% 
  filter(time == "1960")
## Adding missing grouping variables: `name`
ggplot(gdp_1960, aes(GDP_PC, lifeExpectancy, size = totalPopulation/1000000, col = factor(region))) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) +
  labs(x = "GDP Per Capita",
       y = "Life Exepectancy in Years",
       title = "GDP Per Capita vs. Life Ecpectancy in 1960",
       color = "Continent",
       size = "Population in Millions")

Looking at the scatterplot above, Europe and America have the highest GDP per capita which increases their life expectancy’s. This graph shows the relationship between life expectancy and GDP per capita.

Question 4.3

Over the last 60 years, the world has increased its population, thus the life expectancy has increased for each region. Similar to the GDP per capita, it has increased. When we compare these two plots together, it shows us that as the population increases, the GDP per capita and life expectancy increases. However, the overall trend of these two plots remain somewhat similar.

Question 4.5

world %>% 
  select(region, lifeExpectancy, time) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(region), !is.na(lifeExpectancy), !is.na(time)) %>% 
  filter(time %in% c("1960", "2016")) %>% 
  group_by(region, time) %>% 
  summarise(average = mean(lifeExpectancy)) %>% 
  mutate(previous = lag(average), growth = average - previous)

Question 4.6

(6pt) Show the histogram of GDP per capita for years of 1960 and 2019. Try to put both histograms on the same graph, see how well you can do it!

world %>% 
  filter(!is.na(GDP_PC)) %>% 
  filter(time %in% c("1960", "2019")) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(GDP_PC, fill = factor(time))) +
  geom_histogram(alpha = 0.5, position = "dodge", bins = 30) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("pink", "purple"), labels = c("1960", "2019")) +
  labs(x = "GDP Per Capita",
       y = "Count",
       title = "GDP Per Capita in 1960 and 2019")

ranks <- world %>% 
  select(name, lifeExpectancy, time) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(lifeExpectancy), !is.na(name), time %in% c("1960", "2019")) %>% 
  arrange(time, desc(lifeExpectancy)) %>% 
  group_by(time) %>% 
  mutate(rankings = rank(desc(lifeExpectancy)))

ranks %>%
